<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,644]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,365,151,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" reason="1">Comparisons.</emphasis>
In the original comparison of 
<taxonomicName box="[714,885,152,176]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aquilonarius">
<emphasis box="[714,885,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P. aquilonarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with other 
<taxonomicName box="[1018,1289,151,176]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1018,1200,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Perulibatrachus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
the width of the head was said to be greater than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[601,748,188,212]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elminensis">
<emphasis box="[601,748,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P. elminensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Roux" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[806,947,188,212]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rossignoli">
<emphasis box="[806,947,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P. rossignoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both West African species and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Greenfield" authorityYear="1996" box="[1318,1436,188,212]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kilburni">
<emphasis box="[1318,1436,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P. kilburni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from east Africa. The narrower head measurement of the second specimen of 
<taxonomicName box="[1030,1202,224,248]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aquilonarius">
<emphasis box="[1030,1044,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1059,1202,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">aquilonarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is close to the upper limit for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[250,395,260,284]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elminensis">
<emphasis box="[250,395,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P. elminensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(37.1 vs 37.9) and below the greatest width for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Roux" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[932,1071,260,284]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rossignoli">
<emphasis box="[932,1071,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P. rossignoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(37.1 vs. 40.9). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Greenfield" authorityYear="1996" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kilburni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Perulibatrachus kilburni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a head width of 29.7. 
<taxonomicName box="[533,866,296,320]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aquilonarius">
<emphasis box="[533,866,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Perulibatrachus aquilonarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
still, however, differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[1178,1323,296,320]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elminensis">
<emphasis box="[1178,1323,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P.elminensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having fewer anal-fin and pectoral-fin rays. Additionally, now that the fresh coloration is known, 
<taxonomicName box="[1179,1351,332,356]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aquilonarius">
<emphasis box="[1179,1351,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P. aquilonarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clearly differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[291,435,368,392]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elminensis">
<emphasis box="[291,435,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P.elminensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in fresh coloration by having the body and fins covered with small dark spots (
<figureCitation box="[1315,1423,367,391]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 2" captionStart-1="FIGURE 3" captionStart-2="FIGURE 4" captionStartId-0="2.[151,250,1667,1690]" captionStartId-1="3.[151,250,939,962]" captionStartId-2="3.[151,250,1988,2011]" captionTargetBox-0="[217,1369,913,1646]" captionTargetBox-1="[217,1369,193,884]" captionTargetBox-2="[217,1341,1042,1947]" captionTargetId-0="figure-361@2.[217,1369,913,1646]" captionTargetId-1="figure-45@3.[217,1369,193,918]" captionTargetId-2="figure-48@3.[217,1369,1042,1947]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="3" captionTargetPageId-2="3" captionText-0="FIGURE 2. Perulibatrachus aquilonarius, CAS 231007, dorsal view. Photograph by K.K. Bineesh." captionText-1="FIGURE 3. Perulibatrachus aquilonarius, CAS 231007, front view of head. Photograph by K.K. Bineesh." captionText-2="FIGURE 4. Perulibatrachus aquilonarius, CAS 231007, side view of head. Photograph by K.K. Bineesh." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285467" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285469" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285471" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5285467/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5285469/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/5285471/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Figs. 2–4</figureCitation>
), whereas 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[249,394,404,428]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elminensis">
<emphasis box="[249,394,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P. elminensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a network of irregular brown lines covering the body (
<figureCitation box="[1049,1118,404,428]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1148,1171]" captionTargetBox="[409,1177,700,1127]" captionTargetId="figure-364@4.[409,1177,700,1128]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. Perulibatrachus elminensis, 21cm TL, Ivory Coast. Photograph by A. Oddgeir." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5285473/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). It no longer differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Roux" baseAuthorityYear="1957" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rossignoli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P. rossignoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the number of pectoral-fin rays, but still differs in having fewer dorsal-fin rays and also in color: Whereas 
<taxonomicName box="[255,425,476,500]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aquilonarius">
<emphasis box="[255,425,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P. aquilonarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is covered with many small dark spots, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Roux" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[870,1008,476,500]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Batrachoididae" genus="Perulibatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Batrachoidiformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rossignoli">
<emphasis box="[870,1008,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">P. rossignoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has several large blotches on the body and no spotting on the fins (
<figureCitation box="[464,532,511,535]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1640,1663]" captionTargetBox="[217,1369,1220,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-367@4.[217,1369,1220,1617]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 6. Perulibatrachus rossignoli, 20 cm TL, Ghana. Photograph by A. Oddgeir." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5285475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,644]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,548,572]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
The second specimen was collected off the coast of Tuticorin in the Gulf of Mannar at a depth of 
<quantity box="[151,243,583,607]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" unit="m" value="20.0" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="10.0">10–30m</quantity>
by a gill net. The 
<typeStatus box="[447,545,583,607]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected at Madas to the north of Tuticorin, also along the southeast coast of 
<collectingCountry box="[181,242,620,644]" name="India" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">India</collectingCountry>
. This species may prove to be more widespread along the Indian coast.
</paragraph>
